### Technical

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} is also used in many technical applications:

as an adhesive in glue stick and hot-melt adhesives

as a special additive for batteries, ceramics, fiberglass, inks, and inkjet paper, and in the chemical-mechanical planarization process

as an emulsifier and disintegrant for {{ drug.dosage_form }} polymerization

to increase resolution in photoresists for cathode ray tubes ({{ drug.molecular_formula }})

in aqueous metal quenching

for production of membranes, such as dialysis and water purification filters

as a binder and complexation agent in agricultural applications such as crop protection, seed treatment and coating

as a thickening agent in tooth whitening gels

as an aid for increasing the solubility of drugs in liquid and semi-liquid dosage forms (syrups, soft gelatine {{ drug.dosage_form }}) and as an inhibitor of recrystallisation

as an additive to Doro's {{ drug.molecular_formula }} extraction buffer

as a liquid-phase dispersion enhancing agent in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.molecular_formula }}

as a surfactant, reducing agent, shape controlling agent and dispersant in nanoparticle synthesis and their self-assembly

as a stabilizing agent in all inorganic solar cells

Other uses

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} binds to polar molecules exceptionally well, owing to its polarity. This has led to its application in coatings for photo-quality ink-jet papers and transparencies, as well as in inks for inkjet printers.

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} is also used in personal care products, such as shampoos and toothpastes, in paints, and adhesives that must be moistened, such as old-style postage stamps and envelopes. It has also been used in contact lens solutions and in steel-quenching solutions.[14][15] {{ drug.molecular_formula }} is the basis of the early formulas for hair sprays and hair gels, and still continues to be a component of some.

As a food additive, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} is a stabilizer and has E number E1201. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} (crospovidone) is E1202. It is also used in the wine industry as a fining agent for white wine and some beers.

In molecular biology, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} can be used as a blocking agent during Southern blot analysis as a component of Denhardt's buffer. It is also exceptionally good at absorbing polyphenols during {{ drug.molecular_formula }} purification. Polyphenols are common in many plant tissues and can deactivate proteins if not removed and therefore inhibit many downstream reactions like {{ drug.molecular_formula }}.

In microscopy, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} is useful for making an aqueous mounting medium.[16]

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} can be used to screen for phenolic properties, as referenced in a 2000 study on the effect of plant extracts on insulin production.

Safety

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) has approved this chemical for many uses,[18] and it is generally considered safe. However, there have been documented cases of allergic reactions to {{ drug.molecular_formula }}/povidone, particularly regarding {{ drug.route_of_administration }} (applied under the skin) use and situations where the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} has come in contact with autologous serum(internal blood fluids) and mucous membranes. For example, a boy having an anaphylactic response after application of {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-Iodine for treatment of impetigo was found to be allergicto the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} component of the {{ drug.dosage_form }}.[19] A woman, who had previously experienced urticaria (hives) from various hair products, later found to contain {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, had an anaphylacticresponse after povidone-iodine {{ drug.dosage_form }} was applied internally. She was found to be allergic to {{ drug.molecular_formula }}.[20] In another case, a man experiencing anaphylaxis after taking acetaminophentablets orally was found to be allergic to {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. Povidone is commonly used in conjunction with other chemicals. Some of these, such as iodine, are blamed for allergic responses, although testing results in some patients show no signs of allergy to the suspect chemical. Allergies attributed to these other chemicals may possibly be caused by the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} instead.

Properties

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} is soluble in water and other polar solvents. For example, it is soluble in various alcohols, such as methanol and ethanol, as well as in more exotic solvents like the deep eutectic solvent formed by choline chloride and urea (Relin).[25] When dry it is a light flaky hygroscopic powder, readily absorbing up to 40% of its weight in atmospheric water. In {{ drug.dosage_form }}, it has excellent wetting properties and readily forms films. This makes it good as a coating or an additive to coatings.

A 2014 study found fluorescent properties of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and its oxidized hydrolyzate.

History

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} was first synthesized by Walter Reppe and a patent was filed in 1939 for one of the derivatives of acetylene chemistry. {{ drug.molecular_formula }} was initially used as a blood plasma substitute and later in a wide variety of applications in medicine, pharmacy, cosmetics and industrial production..
